data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **Cosmos DB provider removes synchronous API support entirely**. The sync-over-async opt-in (e.g., `EnableSyncOverAsync()` on `UseCosmos(...)`) is gone — it was a temporary bridge, not a long-term solution.

Every call in your repository will throw **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime:

| Breaks | Replace with |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `await .ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(...)` | `await .FirstAsync(...)` |
| `.Count()` | `await .CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `await .SaveChangesAsync()` |

### Migrated version

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- This is Cosmos-specific — the relational providers (SQL Server, PostgreSQL, etc.) still support sync APIs.
- Callers of these methods must also be updated to `await` the results, so the async propagation ripples up the call stack.
- Remove the `EnableSyncOverAsync()` config line from your `DbContext` setup — it will no longer compile.
